AB  - This dissertation provides a critical evaluation of Gerald Caplan's Consultee-Centered Case Consultation (CCCC) potential usefulness to help foster parents work more effectively with foster children's issues, enhance development foster parent child attachment security, and reduce factors that contribute to disruption of placement situations. Many researchers and clinicians have discussed the importance of and the difficulties that often characterize the foster parent-child relationship (Sandow, 1998; Hallas, 2000; McQuaid, 1995; Bennett, 2000; Phillips, 2001; Denby et al, 1999; Marcus, 1999). While great strides have been made describing the factors contributing to success or failure in foster parent-child relationships, viable interventions to prevent placement disruptions have not been offered. Proch and Taber (1987) found that foster care disruption of placement typically occurs due to reciprocal alienation and mutually rejecting interactions between child and caregivers. It is an intervention based on the resolution of problematic interactions within the foster parent-child relationship, rather than on a narrow focus on the child's behavior that will most likely be beneficial in disruption of placement situations. An intervention that could be utilized to focus on the foster parents' responses to factors that contribute to disruption of placement is CCCC. The CCCC intervention was developed to work with various kinds of caregiving professionals who in particular situations have old unresolved conflicts from their past reemerge when faced with a client who has similar problems. To date no theoretical analysis or research has been done to determine whether the CCCC model could be applied to foster parenting difficulties. John Bowlby's theory of attachment involving the constructs of internal working models and attachment classifications (Ainsworth, 1978 and Main, 1986) provides a theoretical perspective to understand how parent-child relationships operate and how the CCCC intervention model, when understood through the lens of attachment theory, could provide a vital and effective approach to managing disruption of placement difficulties in the foster parent-child relationship. This dissertation provides an extensive literature review of the significant factors involved in developing and maintaining attachment security between foster parents and children, the role of attachment theory in foster parent-child relationships and Caplan's Consultee-centered case consultation model. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
