AB  - International adoption has been increasing since the 1960s and is now an important social issue. The majority of these adoptions take place in good conditions but some can be a source of great suffering for the new family. This study seeks out elements indicative of traumatic experiences in adoptive parents' accounts, especially during their first encounter with their child in situations of international adoption. We carried out a review of the literature concerning trauma narratives in order to find which characteristics in the structure of the account are present to a significantly higher degree among traumatized individuals as compared to healthy subjects. We added « lack of coherence » in the account, described according to the paradigm of attachment, measured by Edicode. These characteristics are called « traumatic markers ». Among the seven accounts collected in a clinical population of families in treatment in a consultation specialized in adoption, all contain traumatic markers in their structure. Moreover, the analysis of content in these narratives allows us to suggest areas for reflection concerning international adoption. The recognition of traumatic markers in the stories makes it possible to elaborate, and then to go beyond such markers so as to create a specific, vitalized bond between the parents and their child. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2019 APA, all rights reserved)
