AB  - Reviews the book, Psychotherapy with infants and young children: Repairing the effects of stress and trauma on early attachment by Alicia F. Lieberman and Patricia Van Horn (see record [rid]2008-06757-000[/rid]). This book provides a comprehensive overview of Child-Parent Psychotherapy (CPP). The authors demonstrate that CPP is a robust theory with practical applications for the mental health treatment of all young children from birth through age 5 years. They continue by describing CPP treatment strategies, with a focus on cultural considerations in treatment. They emphasize the importance of core competencies of the effective CPP clinician, explain the theory behind CPP intervention modalities, and provide CPP clinicians with guidelines on translating theory into practice. An interesting perspective provided in the discussion of therapeutic lapses in attunement addresses common mistakes made by therapists practicing CPP and emphasizes the importance of reflective supervision. Specific issues such as mandated treatment, limits of confidentiality, and CPP with foster parents are presented, which provides a practical resource for clinicians working in these settings. The authors emphasize in their conclusion that their book is not intended to prescribe specific treatment steps but rather to help clinicians develop clinical reasoning within the theoretical context of CPP. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
