AB  - Most readers will know that a culture and ideas battle is underway within clinical professions and workplaces, around what kinds of knowledge one should use to guide practice. To date, there is remarkably little evidence that existing mental health interventions are effective for children with complex attachment- and trauma-related difficulties. This is not to say that there are no effective interventions. Rather, the present standards, which rate psychotherapy are disconnected from the reality of assisting children with complex difficulties in real-world clinical settings. It is believed that mental health intervention evidence ratings should be based on multiple evidence requirements. Well-designed (randomized controlled trials) RCTs have exceptional methodological rigor and internal validity. No other research design adequately isolates treatment effects from a myriad of potential biases that create an illusion of effectiveness. Few examples of how future psychotherapy RCTs can become more robust are also discusses. Dedicated mental health services for maltreated children, children in care, and adopted children are well placed to lead the push for change, given their specialized knowledge of complex attachment- and trauma-related difficulties. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
